Fix the Hyprland cursor falling back to a default/generic cursor on classic-laddie (and any host using this home profile) by generating a hyprcursor-format theme for the configured Bibata cursor.

ROOT CAUSE (verified on the live system):
- Cursor is configured in `home/desktop.nix` via `home.pointerCursor` as `Bibata-Modern-Ice` (package `pkgs.bibata-cursors`), but ONLY as an XCursor theme — `gtk.enable = true` is set, there is NO `hyprcursor.enable`. The `bibata-cursors` package ships XCursor format only (cursors/, index.theme; no manifest.hl / hyprcursor data).
- Hyprland 0.55.4 (current version on the host) uses hyprcursor BY DEFAULT (`cursor:enable_hyprcursor = 1`, confirmed via hyprctl). With no hyprcursor theme available, Hyprland cannot resolve Bibata and falls back to its built-in default cursor — this is the 'cursor changed appearance' symptom the user noticed after a reboot activated a system upgrade.

THE FIX:
In `home/desktop.nix`, in the existing `home.pointerCursor` block (currently:
    home.pointerCursor = {
      gtk.enable = true;
      # x11.enable = true;
      package = pkgs.bibata-cursors;
      name = "Bibata-Modern-Ice";
      size = 24;
    };
), add `hyprcursor.enable = true;`. This makes home-manager run hyprcursor-util to convert the Bibata XCursor theme into a hyprcursor theme that Hyprland 0.55 can find, restoring the intended cursor. Keep the existing size = 24 (hyprcursor.size inherits from the top-level size; do not duplicate unless the option requires it). Add a brief comment explaining WHY (Hyprland 0.55 defaults to hyprcursor; Bibata is xcursor-only, so without this it falls back to a default cursor). Match the file's existing 2-space indentation and style.

CONSTRAINTS:
- Change ONLY the `home.pointerCursor` block in `home/desktop.nix`. Do not touch anything else.
- Follow repo conventions (AGENTS.md): Nix, 2-space indent, declarative. No direct commits to main; a PR branch is created for you.

VALIDATION (do BEFORE opening the PR):
- Build the host that uses this home profile: `nix build .#nixosConfigurations.classic-laddie.config.system.build.toplevel` — must succeed (home-manager is integrated as a NixOS module, so this evaluates and builds the home config too).
- Prove the option is set: `nix eval .#nixosConfigurations.classic-laddie.config.home-manager.users.patrick.home.pointerCursor.hyprcursor.enable` (adjust the attr path if the username/home wiring differs) must return true.
- Prove a hyprcursor theme is actually produced (not just the option flipped): inspect the built home-manager generation / home.file set for a generated hyprcursor theme — e.g. a path containing `hyprcursors` or a `manifest.hl` for Bibata-Modern-Ice. Report exactly how you confirmed it in the PR description. If the home-manager version in this flake does NOT provide `home.pointerCursor.hyprcursor.enable`, STOP and instead report that in the PR description with the home-manager version, and implement the equivalent by adding the hyprcursor theme via `home.file`/an `xdg.dataFile` that runs `hyprcursor-util --extract`/convert — but first prefer the built-in option.
- Run any pre-commit hooks / fast `nix flake check` if present and fix failures.
- Do NOT run switch/activate on the running system.

PR DESCRIPTION: summarize the root cause above (Hyprland 0.55 hyprcursor default + xcursor-only Bibata => default-cursor fallback; surfaced when a reboot activated a pending upgrade), the one-line fix, and exactly how you verified the hyprcursor theme is generated. Note that after merge+rebuild the user should re-login (or run `hyprctl setcursor Bibata-Modern-Ice 24`) for it to take effect.
